# Minerva project conventions

## Repository language (remember this)

- **English everywhere** in the repo except localized UX strings: **identifiers**, **comments**, **JSDoc/TSDoc**, **README**, **package.json `description`**, commit messages, and any other developer-facing prose.
- **Only exception:** user-facing copy belongs in **`src/i18n.ts`** (`en` as the canonical dictionary; `es` / `es-AR` for overrides). Components must use `t('key')` for labels, placeholders, `aria-label`s, errors, and markdown shown to users—never hardcoded Spanish/English in JSX/TS outside i18n.

## Documentation

- **README** and any project documentation (markdown in the repo) must be **entirely in English**.

## Internationalization

- **Every user-visible string** must go through i18n: add keys to `src/i18n.ts` for `en`, override in `es` / `es-AR` as needed, and use `createTranslator` / `t('…')` in the UI.
- Do not add hardcoded labels, placeholders, `aria-label`s, or errors in components without a translation key.

## UI and components

- New **components and layouts** must match the **current visual language**: existing CSS variables (`src/index.css`), utility classes in `src/app.css`, spacing, typography, and the established Slate & Electric Blue palette.
- Prefer extending existing patterns (buttons, fields, dialogs, composer) over introducing unrelated frameworks or one-off styling systems.

## Terminology: "chat prompt"

- In this project, **"chat prompt"** means the whole composer area at the bottom of the chat, not just the text input.
- It includes the prompt textarea, send/stop actions, attachment and utility buttons, and visible identity labels (Chat AI / user name) shown in that bottom section.
- When a task mentions changing or syncing something in the "chat prompt", apply it to that full bottom composer section.

## On-device AI affordances

- For **any control that invokes the on-device model** (refine prompt, summaries, titles, etc.), use the shared **`AiActionIcon`** from `src/components/AiActionIcon.tsx` so the sparkle mark stays consistent across the app.

## System AI safety rule

- Treat **System AI** features (auto-title, auto-summary, refine, and any future helper flows) as **optional**.
- If no System AI is selected (`undefined` / "Ninguna"), helper flows must **no-op safely** and never break chat send, message persistence, or UI rendering.
- Guard every System-AI entry point so disabled state degrades gracefully (skip call, keep current flow working, and avoid thrown errors).

## Persistence and backup / restore

- **All durable app state** (chat threads, messages, attachment blobs, language/theme, active session id, and local settings) lives in **IndexedDB** via `src/db.ts` and `src/storage.ts`. Do not add a second source of truth (e.g. `localStorage` for the same fields) without an explicit product decision.
- **Backup / restore** is implemented in **`src/backupRestore.ts`** and must stay aligned with the DB:
  - When you change **`MINERVA_IDB_SCHEMA_VERSION`** in `src/db.ts`, or change object stores / persisted record shapes, **update backup export/import** in `backupRestore.ts` (wire format, validation, or `MINERVA_BACKUP_PAYLOAD_VERSION`) and add any needed **i18n** keys under `settings.backup.*`.
  - New persisted fields should be included in the backup payload (or intentionally documented as excluded with a code comment). **`LocalSettings`** fields (e.g. composer limits) are part of the `settings` row and must remain JSON-serializable and normalized in `storage.ts` / backup import.
- User-facing actions for backup/restore belong under **Settings → Backup** (`#settings-pane-backup` in `App.tsx`), with strings only from **`src/i18n.ts`**.
